Kennedy decided to ban the use
of testing of nuclear weapons in

00:28:35.145 --> 00:28:39.417
the atmosphere that was
resulting in strontium-90 in the

00:28:39.417 --> 00:28:43.518
bones at high concentrations,
particularly among the

00:28:43.518 --> 00:28:45.108
youngest, the children.
 

00:28:45.108 --> 00:28:47.779
Population control has been a
success.

00:28:47.779 --> 00:28:52.396
Compared to the projections of
the 1970s by Paul Ehrlich and

00:28:52.396 --> 00:28:56.958
Julian Simon and others,
it's quite striking that the

00:28:56.958 --> 00:29:01.680
geometric projections have
diminished substantially,

00:29:01.680 --> 00:29:04.558
particularly in developing
parts of the world.

00:29:04.558 --> 00:29:07.948
The phase-out of chlorinated
hydrocarbons,

00:29:07.948 --> 00:29:12.162
including DDT and aldrin and
chlordane and dieldrin,

00:29:12.162 --> 00:29:14.890
heptachlor back in the 1970s.
 

00:29:14.890 --> 00:29:17.096
These became one of the very
first targets of the

00:29:17.096 --> 00:29:18.660
Environmental Protection Agency.
 

00:29:18.660 --> 00:29:21.883
And because they are fat
loving, they're lipophilic,

00:29:21.883 --> 00:29:24.537
they persisted,
they moved through the food

00:29:24.537 --> 00:29:25.170
chain.
 

00:29:25.170 --> 00:29:28.440
They moved into our bodies.
 

00:29:28.440 --> 00:29:31.962
And you and I are still
carrying around residues of many

00:29:31.962 --> 00:29:34.269
of these chlorinated
hydrocarbons.

00:29:34.269 --> 00:29:37.410
Your concentrations are lower
than mine are.

00:29:37.410 --> 00:29:40.980
But your concentrations
predominately came from your

00:29:40.980 --> 00:29:42.730
mother via breast milk.
 

00:29:42.730 --> 00:29:46.616
That's the mechanism of
transfer across generations for

00:29:46.616 --> 00:29:48.490
some of these compounds.
 

00:29:48.490 --> 00:29:51.220
So phasing them out was a very
important thing to do.

00:29:51.220 --> 00:29:54.519
Lead in gasoline and paint were
phased out as well.

00:29:54.519 --> 00:29:59.830
Chlorinated fluorocarbons that
were and are responsible for

00:29:59.830 --> 00:30:04.500
diminishing the ozone layer that
exists in the upper

00:30:04.500 --> 00:30:07.993
stratosphere,
so that reducing CFCs and

00:30:07.993 --> 00:30:12.420
similar ozone-gobbling compounds
has been a success story,

00:30:12.420 --> 00:30:15.808
at least the rate of loss has
been stabilized.

00:30:15.808 --> 00:30:19.200
Polychlorinated biphenyl
reduction,

00:30:19.200 --> 00:30:24.938
these are chemicals originally
thought to be beneficial because

00:30:24.938 --> 00:30:30.584
they acted as a refrigerant and
flame retardant for electronic

00:30:30.584 --> 00:30:34.890
technologies,
such as electrical transformers.

00:30:34.890 --> 00:30:39.608
So that phasing out PCBs that
were building up in the tissues

00:30:39.608 --> 00:30:42.586
of wildlife,
particularly large mammals,

00:30:42.586 --> 00:30:45.219
as well as birds,
and also in human tissues,

00:30:45.219 --> 00:30:47.380
has been a very important
success story.

00:30:47.380 --> 00:30:50.923
Recognizing the threat of
asbestos in producing a very

00:30:50.923 --> 00:30:54.202
rare form of cancer called
mesothelioma was a very

00:30:54.202 --> 00:30:57.250
important step,
as well as the increasing

00:30:57.250 --> 00:31:01.788
restriction on tobacco,
so that we're seeing a decline

00:31:01.788 --> 00:31:06.881
in some forms of lung cancer in
response to the tobacco

00:31:06.881 --> 00:31:08.390
restrictions.
 

00:31:08.390 --> 00:31:12.409
And we're also seeing very
interesting declines in the rate

00:31:12.409 --> 00:31:16.498
of addiction in those parts of
the country where advertising

00:31:16.498 --> 00:31:20.656
has been most heavily restricted
and public service campaigns

00:31:20.656 --> 00:31:25.368
have been mounted to warn people
about the dangers of tobacco.

00:31:25.368 --> 00:31:28.811
We've also made some great
strides in the area of food

00:31:28.811 --> 00:31:32.059
safety, particularly in terms of
reducing microbial

00:31:32.059 --> 00:31:33.230
contamination.
 

00:31:33.230 --> 00:31:38.894
And also, the stellar success
story about the rise of organic

00:31:38.894 --> 00:31:44.750
food I think is something to
take note of and to learn from.

00:31:44.750 --> 00:31:47.988
So what are the most persistent
problems, the ones that have

00:31:47.988 --> 00:31:50.019
been hardest to deal with,
and why?

00:31:50.019 --> 00:31:54.279
Fossil fuel consumption,
renewable energy innovation in

00:31:54.279 --> 00:31:57.750
part due to our lack of
subsidies relative to

00:31:57.750 --> 00:32:02.009
subsidizing fossil fuels as well
as nuclear power.

00:32:02.009 --> 00:32:05.049
Radioactive materials,
the concentration of

00:32:05.049 --> 00:32:09.317
radioactive materials,
particularly for the production

00:32:09.317 --> 00:32:12.198
of weapons,
has created some of the most

00:32:12.198 --> 00:32:14.180
hazardous sites in the world.
 

00:32:14.180 --> 00:32:17.558
So Hanford, Washington,
the Hanford Works in

00:32:17.558 --> 00:32:20.598
Washington,
as well as the Oakridge

00:32:20.598 --> 00:32:24.140
Laboratory or Savannah River in
Georgia,

00:32:24.140 --> 00:32:27.259
these are seriously
contaminated sites.

00:32:27.259 --> 00:32:31.058
Waste management has also been
a persistent problem.

00:32:31.058 --> 00:32:33.788
Our recycling efforts have
clearly failed us.

00:32:33.788 --> 00:32:36.396
Most people don't know the
difference between a plastic

00:32:36.396 --> 00:32:39.003
that is stamped with a number
six and a plastic that is

00:32:39.003 --> 00:32:40.548
stamped with a number three.
 

00:32:40.548 --> 00:32:44.369
And in fact,
I'll challenge you right now to

00:32:44.369 --> 00:32:49.880
go through one week of this term
without buying any plastic.

00:32:49.880 --> 00:32:53.906
And if anybody is capable of
doing that by the end of the

00:32:53.906 --> 00:32:56.640
term, I will take you out for
lunch.

00:32:56.640 --> 00:33:02.692
I've made that offer for the
past five years and I have not

00:33:02.692 --> 00:33:06.660
spent one dime on lunch as a
result.

00:33:06.660 --> 00:33:10.277
Transport, personal transport
as opposed to public transit

00:33:10.277 --> 00:33:13.450
facilities, is a persistent and
growing problem.

00:33:13.450 --> 00:33:16.704
We now have one vehicle in the
United States for every person

00:33:16.704 --> 00:33:18.170
who is eligible to drive.
 

00:33:18.170 --> 00:33:21.470
That's nearly 250 million
vehicles.

00:33:21.470 --> 00:33:24.182
We have more vehicles per
capita in the United States than

00:33:24.182 --> 00:33:25.660
any other place in the world.
 

00:33:25.660 --> 00:33:29.212
And we drive more miles per
person than any place in the

00:33:29.212 --> 00:33:29.730
world.
 

00:33:29.730 --> 00:33:34.151
The failure to develop public
transit facilities is quite

00:33:34.151 --> 00:33:35.019
striking.
 

00:33:35.019 --> 00:33:38.624
Parks and protected areas,
we are not protecting areas the

00:33:38.624 --> 00:33:41.849
way that we were back in the
1970s and the 1980s.

00:33:41.849 --> 00:33:43.630
So why have we slowed down?
 

00:33:43.630 --> 00:33:47.737
Why was the government in the
process of acquiring lands in

00:33:47.737 --> 00:33:51.065
the 1960s, '70s,
and '80s and building parks and

00:33:51.065 --> 00:33:54.038
building large corridors for
wildlife?

00:33:54.038 --> 00:33:57.684
To conserve biological
diversity, but also to provide

00:33:57.684 --> 00:34:00.490
wide-scale recreational
opportunities.

00:34:00.490 --> 00:34:05.730
So why have land acquisition
efforts been stalled?

00:34:05.730 --> 00:34:08.440
Biological diversity loss is
also growing,

00:34:08.440 --> 00:34:12.603
in part because of the chemical
threats that I described earlier

00:34:12.603 --> 00:34:13.860
in the lecture.
 

00:34:13.860 --> 00:34:18.045
There are nearly 450 million
acres of the United States

00:34:18.045 --> 00:34:21.764
landscape that are routinely
sprayed by biocides,

00:34:21.764 --> 00:34:24.710
pesticides of one sort or
another.

00:34:24.710 --> 00:34:28.753
There are 1,000 different
biocides that are each licensed

00:34:28.753 --> 00:34:29.909
independently.
 

00:34:29.909 --> 00:34:33.733
So at that scale,
how could we not think that we

00:34:33.733 --> 00:34:37.070
would be threatening different
species?

00:34:37.070 --> 00:34:39.018
Also agriculture.
 

00:34:39.018 --> 00:34:42.215
One of the great drivers of
loss of biological diversity in

00:34:42.215 --> 00:34:44.420
the world is agricultural
development.

00:34:44.420 --> 00:34:46.980
And you can see this in the
Amazon,

00:34:46.980 --> 00:34:51.474
where tropical rain forests
that are some of the richest and

00:34:51.474 --> 00:34:55.436
most biologically diverse
ecosystems in the world are

00:34:55.436 --> 00:35:00.313
being ripped up and planted with
soybeans for either food or fuel

00:35:00.313 --> 00:35:01.610
production.
 

00:35:01.610 --> 00:35:04.760
So we'll take a look at some of
the key drivers behind

00:35:04.760 --> 00:35:05.949
biodiversity laws.
 

00:35:05.949 --> 00:35:10.126
Marine species exploitation,
we'll take a look at the

00:35:10.126 --> 00:35:13.500
decline of a variety of
commercial fish.

00:35:13.500 --> 00:35:20.641
We'll also be taking a look at
the tendency of large predatory

00:35:20.641 --> 00:35:23.570
fish to absorb mercury.
 

00:35:23.570 --> 00:35:26.250
So mercury is emitted from
power plants.

00:35:26.250 --> 00:35:28.309
It's also emitted from
incinerators.

00:35:28.309 --> 00:35:32.480
It goes into global circulation
just like DDT would.

00:35:32.480 --> 00:35:38.349
It also rains down on the earth
and it bio-accumulates in large

00:35:38.349 --> 00:35:39.960
predatory fish.
 

00:35:39.960 --> 00:35:43.054
By the end of the term,
you'll understand which fish

00:35:43.054 --> 00:35:45.360
are safe and which are not,
and why.

00:35:45.360 --> 00:35:50.032
And you'll also question the
Bush administration's decision

00:35:50.032 --> 00:35:54.302
to lighten the regulation on
mercury emissions and how

00:35:54.302 --> 00:35:58.688
dangerous that has become,
particularly for the youngest

00:35:58.688 --> 00:35:59.469
in society.
 

00:35:59.469 --> 00:36:01.268
We'll take a look at indoor air
quality.

00:36:01.268 --> 00:36:05.527
And one aspect of this issue
that I'm quite interested in is

00:36:05.527 --> 00:36:09.135
the Environmental Protection
Agency spends probably

00:36:09.135 --> 00:36:13.248
ninety-five to ninety-eight
percent of its time and budget

00:36:13.248 --> 00:36:16.856
thinking about the environment
as being the outdoor

00:36:16.856 --> 00:36:18.300
environment.
 

00:36:18.300 --> 00:36:22.177
Whereas we in the United States
now spend on average more than

00:36:22.177 --> 00:36:24.530
ninety percent of our time
indoors.

00:36:24.530 --> 00:36:29.300
And as somebody that is a dad
and cares about the future of

00:36:29.300 --> 00:36:34.070
the environment and human
health, that's got me worried.

00:36:34.070 --> 00:36:37.099
People are spending less time
outside.

00:36:37.099 --> 00:36:43.690
They're experiencing nature at
a lower rate than ever before.

00:36:43.690 --> 00:36:46.860
They are spending more time in
front of computers in indoor

00:36:46.860 --> 00:36:48.610
environments than ever before.
 

00:36:48.610 --> 00:36:52.947
And EPA does not do much to
regulate the environmental

00:36:52.947 --> 00:36:55.650
quality of indoor environments.
 

00:36:55.650 --> 00:37:01.240
So the reasons for that are
sometimes obvious and sometimes

00:37:01.240 --> 00:37:01.820
not.
 

00:37:01.820 --> 00:37:07.273
One clearly is a respect for
privacy and private property

00:37:07.273 --> 00:37:08.150
rights.
 

00:37:08.150 --> 00:37:12.009
But it means that anybody is
allowed to carry chemicals into

00:37:12.009 --> 00:37:15.398
the indoor environment,
including cleansers or

00:37:15.398 --> 00:37:19.619
pesticides or plastics that can
get into their bodies.

00:37:19.619 --> 00:37:23.849
And there is basically no
regulation to prevent that.

00:37:23.849 --> 00:37:27.840
Hazardous sites,
the number of hazardous sites

00:37:27.840 --> 00:37:33.340
now in the United States is more
than 350,000 on EPA's list.

00:37:33.340 --> 00:37:36.679
There are 50,000 different
hazardous sites that have been

00:37:36.679 --> 00:37:40.079
severely contaminated that are
under the jurisdiction,

00:37:40.079 --> 00:37:43.210
meaning the responsibility,
of the Department of Defense,

00:37:43.210 --> 00:37:46.431
the Department of Energy,
and the Department of the

00:37:46.431 --> 00:37:47.139
Interior.
 

00:37:47.139 --> 00:37:51.302
There are 340,000 sites that
are owned in the private sector

00:37:51.302 --> 00:37:54.690
that have been classified by EPA
as hazardous.

00:37:54.690 --> 00:38:00.239
So the rate of cleanup of these
sites is not even one percent of

00:38:00.239 --> 00:38:04.380
the rate of discovery of new
hazardous sites.

00:38:04.380 --> 00:38:09.219
So this problem of basically
disregarding the chemical abuse

00:38:09.219 --> 00:38:13.277
of the landscape,
feeling comfortable to throw

00:38:13.277 --> 00:38:18.456
chemical mixtures out the back
door without concern for their

00:38:18.456 --> 00:38:23.027
persistence and movement,
this is something that your

00:38:23.027 --> 00:38:25.710
generation will have to deal
with.

00:38:25.710 --> 00:38:30.679
Product labeling will also be a
subject that we'll take on.

00:38:30.679 --> 00:38:36.092
Basically, if you look
carefully at product labels,

00:38:36.092 --> 00:38:40.639
you'll see claims of product
effectiveness,

00:38:40.639 --> 00:38:46.920
product appeal associated with
color or functionality.

00:38:46.920 --> 00:38:51.949
You will not see much in the
way of claims or a demonstration

00:38:51.949 --> 00:38:57.230
of hazard or guidance about how
you might manage the hazards.

00:38:57.230 --> 00:39:00.677
So that product labeling could
be an effective way of conveying

00:39:00.677 --> 00:39:04.201
information to the public,
to inform consumers to make

00:39:04.201 --> 00:39:06.679
choices that are more
responsible.

00:39:06.679 --> 00:39:09.980
So how should we adjust product
labeling law in a way that makes

00:39:09.980 --> 00:39:10.400
sense?
 

00:39:10.400 --> 00:39:13.380
I asked this question with
respect to pesticides several

00:39:13.380 --> 00:39:16.090
years ago and found something
quite interesting.

00:39:16.090 --> 00:39:21.891
If you look at a pesticide bag,
for example a fertilizer bag in

00:39:21.891 --> 00:39:23.670
say a Home Depot.
 

00:39:23.670 --> 00:39:26.739
You'll see the green lawn with
the children playing on the lawn

00:39:26.739 --> 00:39:28.920
and bright colors on the front
of the bag.

00:39:28.920 --> 00:39:32.940
And then the back of the bag in
print that may be eight point,

00:39:32.940 --> 00:39:36.101
it may be six point in size,
print that I have to take my

00:39:36.101 --> 00:39:39.039
glasses off and get very close
to be able to read.

00:39:39.039 --> 00:39:44.753
The warnings are illegible and
unintelligible to a very large

00:39:44.753 --> 00:39:47.039
proportion of society.
 

00:39:47.039 --> 00:39:49.840
And there are some twelve
percent of the U.S.

00:39:49.840 --> 00:39:53.813
population, not an
insignificant number in a

00:39:53.813 --> 00:39:57.050
population of 310 million
people.

00:39:57.050 --> 00:40:02.422
So ten percent that have no
capacity to read type that is

00:40:02.422 --> 00:40:05.300
less than ten point in font.
 

00:40:05.300 --> 00:40:08.702
That means that those warning
labels could never be effective

00:40:08.702 --> 00:40:09.949
for that population.
 

00:40:09.949 --> 00:40:14.034
If you add on to that
percentage, the group that is

00:40:14.034 --> 00:40:17.137
illiterate,
the group that does not have

00:40:17.137 --> 00:40:21.262
enough education in order to
understand what the risk is and

00:40:21.262 --> 00:40:24.722
how they might manage the risk,
gradually, you get up to a

00:40:24.722 --> 00:40:26.789
percentage that's close to forty
percent of the U.S.

00:40:26.789 --> 00:40:30.969
population does not have the
capacity to understand a message

00:40:30.969 --> 00:40:34.871
of hazard or the capacity to
interpret how to manage that

00:40:34.871 --> 00:40:39.262
hazard in a way that would cause
the environment to be protected

00:40:39.262 --> 00:40:41.909
or human health to be protected.
 

00:40:41.909 --> 00:40:45.601
So the statutes we'll look at,
I'm not going to go through all

00:40:45.601 --> 00:40:48.206
of these now,
but we'll go through the major

00:40:48.206 --> 00:40:49.780
statutes and the book.
 

00:40:49.780 --> 00:40:52.266
Weinberg and Reilly will give
you a very concise,

00:40:52.266 --> 00:40:55.219
quick overview of the key
provisions of these statutes.

00:40:55.219 --> 00:41:00.748
And I will show you how the
statutes apply individually to

00:41:00.748 --> 00:41:02.690
the various cases.
 

00:41:02.690 --> 00:41:04.213
We'll take a look,
not just at the chemical

00:41:04.213 --> 00:41:06.306
management statutes,
but also the federal land and

00:41:06.306 --> 00:41:09.003
resource management statutes,
such as the Wilderness Act,

00:41:09.003 --> 00:41:11.735
the Endangered Species Act,
the National Park Service

00:41:11.735 --> 00:41:14.909
Organic Act,
and several others.

00:41:14.909 --> 00:41:18.070
Additional crucial statutes
that you might not think about

00:41:18.070 --> 00:41:21.119
as being environmental in nature
include patent law,

00:41:21.119 --> 00:41:24.954
governing trade secrecy,
the Freedom of Information Act

00:41:24.954 --> 00:41:28.788
that gives you the right to
request from the government

00:41:28.788 --> 00:41:33.119
information about public policy
or about the environment.

00:41:33.119 --> 00:41:36.632
I'll pause here and just ask
how many of you have made

00:41:36.632 --> 00:41:40.610
requests under the Freedom of
Information Act to a government

00:41:40.610 --> 00:41:41.340
agency?
 

00:41:41.340 --> 00:41:43.039
That's very interesting.
 

00:41:43.039 --> 00:41:46.096
The majority of people that do
that in society are highly

00:41:46.096 --> 00:41:46.860
specialized.
 

00:41:46.860 --> 00:41:49.643
They work in the private sector
or they are lawyers,

00:41:49.643 --> 00:41:52.210
they're using them as the basis
for lawsuits.

00:41:52.210 --> 00:41:56.418
So the Freedom of Information
Act was intended to democratize

00:41:56.418 --> 00:42:00.347
information that was held inside
libraries and government

00:42:00.347 --> 00:42:01.260
agencies.
 

00:42:01.260 --> 00:42:04.193
But it's been highly
ineffective in a variety of

00:42:04.193 --> 00:42:04.630
ways.
 

00:42:04.630 --> 00:42:07.059
The National Security Act,
the War Powers Act,

00:42:07.059 --> 00:42:09.989
the Administrative Procedures
Act, Homeland Security,

00:42:09.989 --> 00:42:13.639
the Patriot Act,
and different budget statutes,

00:42:13.639 --> 00:42:19.932
ranging from subsidies to
authorizations for funding for

00:42:19.932 --> 00:42:20.619
EPA.
 

00:42:20.619 --> 00:42:23.780
And these statutes are
absolutely crucial.

00:42:23.780 --> 00:42:29.452
So you can imagine a law being
passed, that -- let's say the

00:42:29.452 --> 00:42:34.739
law had the intent to protect
the environment from a new

00:42:34.739 --> 00:42:36.760
plastic compound.
 

00:42:36.760 --> 00:42:41.507
So that law might be passed and
it might demand that the

00:42:41.507 --> 00:42:44.268
chemical be tested thoroughly.
 

00:42:44.268 --> 00:42:48.550
It might demand that it be
labeled in a way that would

00:42:48.550 --> 00:42:52.670
ensure that it would be managed
more effectively.

00:42:52.670 --> 00:42:58.389
It might assign penalties for
deviance.

00:42:58.389 --> 00:43:02.159
But in Congress,
if Congress doesn't allocate

00:43:02.159 --> 00:43:05.760
the money to EPA,
the program will fail.

00:43:05.760 --> 00:43:10.041
So the industry recognizes this
quite clearly,

00:43:10.041 --> 00:43:15.369
that they have not lost the
battle if a law is passed.

00:43:15.369 --> 00:43:18.628
They will have an opportunity
year after year to go back to

00:43:18.628 --> 00:43:21.717
Congress and try to block
allocation for monitoring that

00:43:21.717 --> 00:43:23.739
issue, for enforcing that issue.
 

00:43:23.739 --> 00:43:27.280
And that explains a lot of the
ineffectiveness of twentieth

00:43:27.280 --> 00:43:28.989
century environmental law.
 

00:43:28.989 --> 00:43:32.686
So on Thursday,
we'll come back to a discussion

00:43:32.686 --> 00:43:36.623
about different types of
strategies to protect the

